<br>
As I walked away, I took a look back to see my father with his arms crossed and my brothers practicing their spell casting.  They were much smarter than I.  One could quickly advance the time it takes to recover from battle, and the other could make bones walk.  I was very impressed with their skills and hoped that one day I could use my own skills to be worth something in battle to them.  <br>
<br>
I strolled over a hill with a heavy, rusted over, two handed sword and a backpack filled with various things.  Father said they would increase my strength.  At the base of the hill I saw a strange sight.  Four humans sat around a fire, eating and drinking, and being very loud.  I had never seen a human before, but the description my family gave of them fit perfectly.  It wasn't long before they realized I was watching them.  All of them stood up and started stumbling in my direction.  Some of them unleashed weapons, and that's when I ran back to my father.  The humans followed me all the way back.  <br>
    My father told me, &quot;If we should fail to win this battle, return to our forest, and the eternal darkness will protect you.  Now go hide, quickly!&quot;  I ran as fast as I could to a distant tree.  Little did I know that was the last thing my father would ever say to me.  I could still see shadows of the humans and my family.  I could only watch as the vicious battle began.  I had hoped that the state in which the humans were in would sway the advantage to our side.  I was brutally wrong.  The humans were advanced and skilled warriors and it seemed their drink gave them an edge.  In pure horror, I witnessed what was left of my family be slain in cold blood.  <br>
<br>
The humans left in a boisterous manner, never bothering to take anything from the recently dead.  I creeped up to the bodies.  There lying in a blanket of death, were my two brothers and my father.  The anger swelled within me.  I stabbed my old sword in the ground.  I opened my father's hand and took his sword into my own.  As I tightly gripped the handle, shadows began to flicker around the blade.  The metal no longer glissoned in the noon-day sun, but instead shadowed everything around it.  The sword absorbed my pain.  This containment caused the metal to turn black.  I sheathed the weapon and placed it on my back.  I also gathered some supplies and took &quot;The Word of Innoruuk&quot; from my father's back pocket.  I stood and whispered a short goodbye.  Not fully knowing my final destination, I started to run to where I felt most at home.  Nektulos.  Thoughts of my mother darted through my head.  Could she still be alive somewhere?  The notion of being strong had left.  I ran swift with the wind in my hair, as crimson tears of hatred screamed down my face.  <br>
